Fun story: Twitter didn't pick 280 as a doubling of 140. We did an analysis of why Japanese users were tweeting more than American users. And we found American users had a huge spike of tweets at 139-140 characters while Japanese had a more gradual distribution

it turns out Japanese had a higher information density per character so 140 chars in Japanese is way more than 140 in English (might be butchering this description)

a data scientist extrapolated how many chars in English would map to 140 in JP - and the answer is 279
Instead of picking 279, Twitter just went with 280. And magically the curve changed to look exactly like the Japanese curve. And overall network behavior didn't change.
see the graph in this post - that triggered this whole change https://blog.twitter.com/en_us/topics/product/2017/Giving-you-more-characters-to-express-yourself
Twitter also felt Japanese behavior was "healthier" (in case folks are wondering why Twitter didn't cut the character limit for Japan instead)
not at all - actually never heard of that incident. was purely due to this Japan analysis.
